## Issue 3: Documentation - Missing Guide for Server Components with TypeScript

**Title:** `Docs: Add comprehensive guide for Server Components with TypeScript`

**Body:**

```markdown
## What documentation is missing?

The current documentation for Server Components lacks comprehensive TypeScript examples and guidance. Many developers are struggling with:

1. How to properly type Server Components vs Client Components
2. How to handle async Server Components with TypeScript
3. How to type props passed from Server to Client Components
4. How to handle serializable types across server/client boundary

## Where should it be added?

- [ ] Getting Started
- [x] API Reference
- [x] Guides
- [ ] Examples

## Suggested content

### Proposed Guide Structure:

```markdown
# TypeScript with Server Components

## Overview
Server Components in React 19 can be async and run on the server. This guide covers TypeScript patterns.

## Basic Server Component Typing

```tsx
// app/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { UserList } from '@/components/UserList';

// Server Components can be async
async function Page() {
  const users = await fetchUsers(); // Server-side fetch

  return <UserList users={users} />;
}

export default Page;
```

## Typing Props for Server/Client Boundary

```tsx
// types/user.ts
export interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  createdAt: Date; // Note: Date is NOT serializable
}

// components/UserList.tsx (Client Component)
'use client';

import { User } from '@/types/user';

interface UserListProps {
  users: User[]; // This will fail - Date is not serializable
}

export function UserList({ users }: UserListProps) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

## Correct Serializable Types

```tsx
// types/user.ts
export interface SerializedUser {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  createdAt: string; // ISO string instead of Date
}

// lib/serialize.ts
export function serializeDate(date: Date): string {
  return date.toISOString();
}
```

## Common Patterns

### Pattern 1: Async Data Fetching
### Pattern 2: Form Handling
### Pattern 3: Real-time Updates

## Why is this important?

- TypeScript is used by 78.9% of React developers (2024 State of JS survey)
- Server Components are a major paradigm shift
- Lack of clear TypeScript guidance leads to common mistakes
- Would reduce support issues and Stack Overflow questions
```

